[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 4. Nf3...."]
[Black "French: Exchange"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 { The French Defense } 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5
{ This is the French Defense: Exchange Variation. Here you see the base position for all the variations you will be learning in this book. This position is even and symmetrical, which means you should look at it as a free opportunity to push for a win with little risk as the Black pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 4. Nf3...."]
[Black "4. Nf3... 5. Bd3... 7. Bg5..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nf3
{ This is what you will see most commonly. Often the best way to keep winning chances is to stop the position from being completely symmetrical. }
1... Bd6
{ The development is natural, points towards White's kingside, and keeps everything else flexible. }
2. Bd3
{ Often White will try to keep this symmetrical. Both bishops are on good squares. }
2... Ne7
{ With this move Black breaks the symmetry, clears the way to castle, and protects the important f5 square. }
3. O-O O-O 4. Bg5 f6
{ White cannot easily attack on the slightly weakened light squares, and the bishop has no useful squares to back up to. }
5. Bh4 Bf5
{ Try to keep the tension between the bishops, and let White capture first. This will allow you to replace your bishop with a strong knight. }
