[Black "4. Nf3... 5. Bd3... 7. Re1..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nf3
{ This is what you will see most commonly. Often the best way to keep winning chances is to stop the position from being completely symmetrical. }
1... Bd6
{ The development of the bishop is natural as it points towards White's kingside, and keeps everything else flexible. }
2. Bd3
{ Often White will try to keep the position symmetrical. Both bishops are on good squares. }
2... Ne7
{ Here Black breaks the symmetry, clears the way to castle, and protects the important f5 square. }
3. O-O O-O
{ And this is as far as you need to know at this point. Black's plan is to trade light squared bishops, but let White capture first. Then you can decide whether to play for a c5 break or Nc6, the a-pawn can be pushed to cramp White's queenside. You can also fight for the e file with Re8. You will get a better feel for which of the possible plans you like most as you learn the rest of the variations. }
4. Re1 c6
{ This move solidifies the d5 pawn and opens up the option for our queen to swing to the queenside later in the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 4. Nf3...."]
[Black "4. Nf3...5. c4...6. Nc3..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nf3
{ This is what you will see most commonly. Often the best way to keep winning chances is to stop the position from being completely symmetrical. }
1... Bd6
{ As learned in the previous variation, staying away from symmetrical knights and staying flexible. }
2. c4
{ The French exchange can be played for a win from both sides, and here White creates tension in the center and tries to take a space advantage. You should be happy to see this because now you do not have to fight to unbalance the position. }
2... Nf6
{ Wait, I thought we weren't going to have symmetrical knights? The goal is an unbalanced position and White has done that for us with the move c4. Here we play our knight to f6 because the center may open up soon and we want our pieces as mobile as possible, and with white not ready to castle you should already be thinking about how you can get something going on the e file. }
3. Nc3 O-O
{ Here it is easy to see how black can play for a win, with an e file he can get to first, a light squared bishop which can be developed with ease, a queenside knight that has 2 good options to develop to, and a possible c pawn break held in reserve. You do not need to be scared of white pushing c5, just retreat your bishop and play b6 and you have an unbalanced queenside. }
4. cxd5 h6
{ Stopping the annoying Bg5. Black will be able to get the d-pawn back without too much effort within the next few moves. }
5. Be2 Nbd7 6. O-O Nb6
{ Targeting the d pawn and moving out of the way of our own light squared bishop. }
7. Ne5 Nbxd5
{ White is left with an isolated pawn and our development is almost complete. }
*

