[SetUp "1"]

1. Nf3
{ This is what you will see most commonly. Often the best way to keep winning chances is to stop the position from being completely symmetrical. }
1... Bd6
{ As learned in the previous variation, staying away from symmetrical knights and staying flexible. }
2. c4
{ The French exchange can be played for a win from both sides, and here White creates tension in the center and tries to take a space advantage. You should be happy to see this because now you do not have to fight to unbalance the position. }
2... Nf6
{ The goal is an unbalanced position and White has done that for us with the move c4. Here we play our knight to f6 because the center may open up soon and we want our pieces as mobile as possible, and with white not ready to castle you should already be thinking about how you can get something going on the e file. }
3. c5 { While this move looks scary its nothing to be afraid of. } 3... Be7
{ We simply back up to another useful square and now we have the bonus of some over-extended White pawns to target. }
4. Bd3 b6 { Immediately attacking the potentially weak pawns. } 5. cxb6 axb6
{ Now we have an open a file to use and should be able to get in an easy and useful c5 pawn break whenever we want. }
6. O-O O-O *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 4. Bd3...."]
[Black "4. Bd3... 5. dxc5..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bd3
{ In the previous chapter we saw white could unbalance the position after we played Bd6 by playing c4. Keeping in mind that our goal is to get an unbalanced position you should not be surprised by black's next move. }
1... c5
{ A c5 break is an important idea in many openings as Black since it provides counterplay and frees Black's pieces. The risk in any unbalanced position is that it becomes sharper. That means that its easier to win or lose the game in just one move because tactics are more prevalent. As a result we need to be ready to respond to several moves for White here if we are going to be tournament ready. }
2. dxc5
{ Surprisingly often White simply takes the pawn. Black has an isolated d pawn buts lots of active pieces and easy development. }
2... Bxc5
{ The natural move, no reason to give White a chance to try to defend the pawn. Especially since we want to castle and contest the e file quickly. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ As mentioned before, in a position that is already unbalanced our knight most often will want to be on f6 so that all our pieces have the maximum mobility. If you are looking for winning chances for Black then you should be happy with this position. Both sides have lots of options. }
4. O-O O-O 5. Bg5 Nc6
{ Since we have the isolated pawn we need our pieces to be as active as possible, so we are choosing not to block our bishop on c8. }
