[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 4. Bd3...."]
[Black "4. Bd3... 5. c3... 6. Nf3..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bd3 c5
{ A c5 break is an important idea in many openings as Black since it provides counterplay and frees Black's pieces. The risk in any unbalanced position is that it becomes sharper. That means that its easier to win or lose the game in just one move because tactics are more prevalent. As a result we need to be ready to respond to several moves for White here if we are going to be tournament ready. }
2. c3
{ White just solidifies their d4 pawn. Since white can still take on c5 we want to wait to move our dark squared bishop if possible, that way we do not have to move it a second time to recapture on c5. Something we haven't talked about much is why c5 unbalances the position. c5 not only makes the pawn structure no longer symmetrical, but it also pressures the d4 pawn. How can we ramp up the pressure on d4? }
2... Nc6
{ The only move that adds pressure to d4. Black will likely run out of moves and need to play Bd6 soon to get castled, but don't worry at this point it isn't considered strong for white to take on c5 once Bd6 is played. }
3. Nf3 Bd6 4. O-O Nge7 { Getting ready to castle ourself } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 4. c4...."]
[Black "4. c4... 5. Nc3... 6. Nf3... 7. Be2..."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. c4
{ White goes for an imbalance immediately. I think that this is a good option for White, but if Black is prepared there are no real issues here and both sides have chances to play for a win. }
1... Nf6
{ The position is already imbalanced so you know where the knight belongs. } 2.
Nc3
{ This move should not be a surprise, adding pressure to d5. We did the same thing as black last chapter. }
2... Be7
{ White has yet to start kingside development so we want to go after the e file quickly and grab a lead in development. }
3. Nf3
{ Getting the kingside development started. We will look at if White plays Bd3 later. }
3... O-O { Completing kingside development and looking to get to the e file }
4. Be2
{ Blocking the e file and preparing to castle. We will look at if White plays Bd3 here later on. }
4... dxc4
{ This forces White to move the light squared bishop again and reopening the e file. }
5. Bxc4 Bd6
{ This move may initially look weird, but its not really a wasted tempo since we just made White move their bishop twice. We reopen the e file, and since White now has an isolated d-pawn our bishop is stable on d6 and helps control e5. }
6. O-O Nc6
{ We are putting our knight in front of our c pawn here because we are trying to target the isolated pawn. The position is already unbalanced and our pieces are free to move, so c5 is not necessary. Nd7 would needlessly block our lightsquared bishop. }
7. h3 { preventing Bg4 } 7... h6
{ Preventing Bg5. Now you have a position where you can comfortably play against the isolated pawn. Without going into too much detail here on how to play against isolated pawns. Trading minors is often good, control the d5 square in front of the pawn, and in the long term try to win the d-pawn without letting white get a big attack. }
*

