1. c4
{ White goes for an imbalance immediately. I think that this is a good option for White, but if Black is prepared there are no real issues here and both sides have chances to play for a win. }
1... Nf6
{ The position is already imbalanced so you know where the knight belongs. } 2.
Nf3
{ You are going to see this less often than Nc3, but if you plan on playing this in tournaments or make these lines your main weapon as black, then you want to be familiar with Nf3. }
2... Bd6
{ Since White did not amp up the pressure on our d5 pawn we can develop our bishop to d6 in one move, instead of 2 like previous lines. }
3. Nc3 O-O
{ The positions should start to look familiar now. This is even better for black because white is not ready to castle so it feels like we are a move ahead. Ready to take the e file or take on c4. Note that we are not currently very worried about our d pawn. White is behind in development and if he takes on d5 the d pawns for white are doubled and isolated making them easy targets for the active black pieces if you want the pawn back. Often I do not go regaining the pawn as black, but instead try to use the lead in development to launch an attack. }
4. cxd5 h6 { Stopping Bg5, we can always get our d-pawn back later. } *

