1. Nc3
{ Here White kind of transposes to a delayed Winawer. It is not quite the same because without a pawn on e5 White does not get the same space advantage as they would in the main line Winawer. }
1... Bb4
{ This pin is extra strong with the pawn still on c2 for white. I propose this move as I am a proponent of the Winawer in general. White has 3 main responses at this point and we will take a brief look at each. Even if you do not normally play the Winawer it is worth learning these lines because you get a lot of play still, but will have even less risk that if White played the mainline Winawer, which is 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4. 4.e5 }
2. Bd3
{ This is by far the most common response you will see. White gets their bishop to d3 without leaving black the chance to capture on c4 like we saw in the previous chapter. }
2... Nc6
{ Unprotected d pawn, lets attack it and develop at the same time. White is forced to protect it or lash out somewhere else. }
3. Ne2 { Choosing to guard the d pawn } 3... Nge7
{ again keeping the option of Bf5 open. If Bg5 is ever played f6 is an easy response. }
4. O-O Bg4
{ While white can play f3 it induces a weakness, then we are free to go to f5 with our bishop. Notice that our bishop can move to a useful square after f3, while White's bishop does not have a useful square after Bg5 and f6. }
5. f3 Bf5
{ Black has no weaknesses and the pawns are not symmetrical. While the position is basically equal, black can play with no risk, with f3 being played means white's kindside is weaker than black's kingside. }
